When Pack looked at how the pair had fared on the P.V.T.—the measure of sleep deprivation used in his earlier study—he found that the twin carrying the mutation significantly outperformed his brother. When the twins were allowed to catch up on the sleep that they had lost in the study, the carrier twin needed far less time to recover—almost a hundred minutes less. Here, then, was a genetic variant that appeared to allow its carriers to derive the same benefit from six hours of sleep as the vast majority of us gets from eight.

Penn-led Team Prevents Memory Problems Caused by Sleep Deprivation

In a new study, published in the Journal of Neuroscience, a team led by scientists from the University of Pennsylvania found that a particular set of cells in a small region of the brain are responsible for memory problems after sleep loss. By selectively increasing levels of a signaling molecule in these cells, the researchers prevented mice from having memory deficits.
